defs.docs: This crate provides a type for representing a syntactically valid, unique account identifier on the [NEAR](https://near.org) network.

attributes.value: / This crate provides a type for representing a syntactically valid, unique account identifier on the [NEAR](https://near.org) network.
/ - An **Account ID** consists of **Account ID parts** separated by `.`, example:
/ - Must not start or end with separators (`_`, `-` or `.`):
/ - Each part of the **Account ID** consists of lowercase alphanumeric symbols separated either by `_` or `-`, example:
/ - Separators are not permitted to immediately follow each other, example:
/ - An **Account ID** that is 64 characters long and consists of lowercase hex characters is a specific **implicit account ID**

defs.name: ParseAccountError
defs.docs: An error which can be returned when parsing a NEAR Account ID.

attributes.value: / An error which can be returned when parsing a NEAR Account ID.

defs.name: kind
defs.docs: Returns the specific cause why parsing the Account ID failed.

attributes.value: / Returns the specific cause why parsing the Account ID failed.

defs.name: TooLong
defs.docs: The Account ID is too long.

attributes.value: / The Account ID is too long.
/ Returned if the `AccountId` is longer than [`AccountId::MAX_LEN`](crate::AccountId::MAX_LEN).

defs.name: TooShort
defs.docs: The Account ID is too short.

attributes.value: / The Account ID is too short.
/ Returned if the `AccountId` is shorter than [`AccountId::MIN_LEN`](crate::AccountId::MIN_LEN).

defs.name: RedundantSeparator
defs.docs: The Account ID has a redundant separator.

attributes.value: / The Account ID has a redundant separator.
/ This variant would be returned if the Account ID either begins with,
/ ends with or has separators immediately following each other.

defs.name: InvalidChar
defs.docs: The Account ID contains an invalid character.

attributes.value: / The Account ID contains an invalid character.
/ This variant would be returned if the Account ID contains an upper-case character, non-separating symbol or space.

defs.name: ParseErrorKind
defs.docs: A list of errors that occur when parsing an invalid Account ID.

attributes.value: / A list of errors that occur when parsing an invalid Account ID.
/ This is a unique, syntactically valid, human-readable account identifier on the NEAR network.
/ [See the crate-level docs for information about validation.](index.html#account-id-rules)

defs.name: MIN_LEN
defs.docs: Shortest valid length for a NEAR Account ID.

attributes.value: / Shortest valid length for a NEAR Account ID.

defs.name: MAX_LEN
defs.docs: Longest valid length for a NEAR Account ID.

attributes.value: / Longest valid length for a NEAR Account ID.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Returns a string slice of the entire Account ID.

attributes.value: / Returns a string slice of the entire Account ID.

defs.name: is_top_level
defs.docs: Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a top-level NEAR Account ID.

attributes.value: / Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a top-level NEAR Account ID.
/ // "alice.near" is a sub account of "near" account

defs.name: is_sub_account_of
defs.docs: Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a direct sub-account of the provided parent account.

attributes.value: / Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a direct sub-account of the provided parent account.
/ // While app.alice.near is a sub account of alice.near,
/ // app.alice.near is not a sub account of near

defs.name: is_implicit
defs.docs: Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a 64 characters long hexadecimal.

attributes.value: / Returns `true` if the `AccountId` is a 64 characters long hexadecimal.

defs.name: is_system
defs.docs: Returns `true` if this `AccountId` is the system account.

attributes.value: / Returns `true` if this `AccountId` is the system account.

defs.name: validate
defs.docs: Validates a string as a well-structured NEAR Account ID.

attributes.value: / Validates a string as a well-structured NEAR Account ID.
/ Checks Account ID validity without constructing an `AccountId` instance.
/ If an Account ID has multiple format violations, the first one would be reported.

defs.name: new_unvalidated
defs.docs: Creates an `AccountId` without any validation checks.

attributes.value: / Creates an `AccountId` without any validation checks.
/ Please note that this is restrictively for internal use only. Plus, being behind a feature flag,
/ this could be removed later in the future.
/ Since this skips validation and constructs an `AccountId` regardless,
/ the caller bears the responsibility of ensuring that the Account ID is valid.
/ You can use the [`AccountId::validate`] function sometime after its creation but before it's use.

deprecated(since = "#4440", note =
"AccountId construction without validation is illegal")
